# Tests and fixtures

- Find the build target that owns a test file with
  `./bin/wtest changed <file>` and run exactly that target; fall back to
  `./wbuild tests` only when the mapping says so.
- `*fixture*.w` files are compile-only inputs with asserted diagnostics.
  For pure compile-diagnostic targets (`warning_test`,
  `type_system_error_test`, `array_error_test`, ...) the expected
  messages are `# expect_stderr:` / `# reject_stderr:` / `# expect_fail`
  directive lines in the fixture's own header comment, run by
  `bin/wfixture` (`tools/wfixture.w` documents the syntax and the
  `<fixture>.w.expect` sidecar fallback). Targets that also run the
  produced binary (trap tests, `check_json_test`, ...) still assert via
  `expect_stderr`/`reject_stderr` step fields in `build.json`. Editing a
  fixture usually requires updating the asserted message text in the
  same commit. The automatic edit-check hook deliberately skips fixture
  paths.
- A new end-to-end test needs: the `tests/foo_test.w` program (use
  `lib/assert.w` / `lib/testing.w` helpers), a target in `build.json`,
  and membership in the `tests` umbrella target. `bin/wtest` picks the
  target up from the manifest automatically (literal step references +
  `bin/wv2 deps` import closures); a residue rule in `tools/test_map.w`
  is only needed for coupling the import graph cannot see (run-time
  data files, non-default-arch modules).
- Test programs may use any syntax the current compiler supports (they
  are compiled with `bin/wv2`, not the seed).
